There are some people man. They take a bird, even a penguin, an ostrich, and put it underground in a cage, and wonder why it isn't happy.

Outside incentive is a powerful thing. So how does when get out of this, this bucket? Unions and mass public upset, usually.
It's a funny thing when an asshole who forces too many crabs into a bucket gets his hand clawed at.

So what if you equate this way of thinking with humans? Consider how we are forced to compete to survive. The death game that is capitalism. Where the cheaters win and those not able to cheat are doomed.

The idea that you must pull someone down to get up, or keep them down where everybody else is. It's probably equated with 'survival of the fittest'.
The kids are pretty smart. They said the bucket wasn't the natural habitat of the crab.

The parallels between these two instances is fascinating. Even if I think Hiromi exited stage left a little too soon.

With Hiromi, his whole deal is Judgement. He judges Yuuji based on his values, and when the subject of shibuya comes up, realizes he isn't fit to judge him.
He sits Yuuji down and listens. And doesn't invalidate Yuuji's feelings of guilt.

Junpei attacks his school, riddled with grief and under Mahito's manipulation. Yuuji tries to reason with him, preach about values, and this doesn't work. Yuuji realizes this and concedes, stating he will listen and not Judge Junpei. Then apologizes.

He is our protagonist, so they should. What's interesting is the focus, and the maturity of these instances.
I'm talking about the moment between Yuuji and Junpei, and a moment between Yuuji and Hiromi.

What has always been spectacular about Jujutsu Kaisen is it's writing.
Not that I can pick up on certain subtle nuances, but hey, that's what analysts are for!
Two distinct moments stand out to me, consistent in their motive. Both center around Yuuji.

Yuji is one of Satoru's pillars. And vice versa.

It's distinctly different from how he treats Megumi, but there are similarities.

Someone on here stated that Gojo was paranoid, and while I don't disagree, his desire for comrades, equals who can match and surpass him, is a stronger part of his personality. He wants to depend on others, rather than be a single pillar that others depend on.

Those two are soul sisters. Very alike, both had their worlds rocked, both sought after, both powerful, or potentially powerful. Both feared by paranoid superiors. Gojo empathizes with Yuji, treats him like an equal. Protects him because he wasn't protected.

It kinda makes sense, how Gojo treats Yuji. Havn't read that far, but if Gojo was sheltered then dropped into the jujutsu world to be a powerful weapon that everyone depended on, then him taking special care not to do the same to Yuji makes all the right sense.
